{
  "masechta": "Bava Batra",
  "daf": 148,
  "amud": "",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to Matnat Shchiv Mera: De-Oraisa vs. De-Rabbanan and the Model of Yerusha",
      "display_title": "Matnat Shchiv Mera Intro",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks on the status of matnat shchiv mera and Tosafos's clarification of de-oraisa",
          "display_title": "De-Oraisa Status",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shmuel's ruling on debt transfer and why matnat shchiv mera appears to be de-oraisa",
          "display_title": "Shmuel Debt Transfer",
          "timestamp": "00:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "The yerusha model as the basis for matnat shchiv mera and its distinction from normal kinyan",
          "display_title": "Yerusha Model Foundation",
          "timestamp": "01:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's response that matnat shchiv mera is de-rabbanan but modeled after yerusha",
          "display_title": "Gemara Resolution",
          "timestamp": "02:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Case of Abstract Transfers: Living in a House and Fruit of a Tree",
      "display_title": "Abstract Transfers",
      "timestamp": "02:31",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman's ruling: a shchiv mera cannot transfer non-concrete abstracted benefits like dwelling or future fruit",
          "display_title": "Rav Nachman Ruling",
          "timestamp": "02:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "The requirement to explicitly transfer property itself when trying to grant use or benefit from it",
          "display_title": "Property Transfer Requir…",
          "timestamp": "04:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion on whether matnat shchiv mera can include conditional language and the tension with kinyan vs yerusha models",
          "display_title": "Conditional Language Deb…",
          "timestamp": "05:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tanu Rabbanan: the Gemara's teaching on what concrete transfers are permissible",
          "display_title": "Tanu Rabbanan",
          "timestamp": "06:07"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Power of Matnat Shchiv Mera: Debt Transfer and the Yerusha Model",
      "display_title": "Debt Transfer Power",
      "timestamp": "08:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rava's statement on debt transfer by shchiv mera despite inability to transfer debt in normal kinyan",
          "display_title": "Rava Debt Transfer",
          "timestamp": "08:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Pappa's answer: the yerusha model explains why debts can transfer without a physical shtar",
          "display_title": "Rav Pappa Yerusha Answer",
          "timestamp": "09:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Acha's alternative: ma'amad sheloshtan as a valid kinyan model for debt transfer",
          "display_title": "Rav Acha Alternative",
          "timestamp": "12:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion on debt transfer: matnat shchiv mera works as either yerusha or kinyan model but with limits",
          "display_title": "Debt Transfer Conclusion",
          "timestamp": "13:37"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Splitting Property: When Fruit and Tree Go to Different Recipients",
      "display_title": "Property Splitting",
      "timestamp": "15:55",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Iba'ya lehu: can a shchiv mera split a tree to one person and its fruit to another",
          "display_title": "Tree/Fruit Split Question",
          "timestamp": "15:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "The principle of makom peiri: whether one actually retains partial ownership or merely gives future fruit",
          "display_title": "Makom Peiri Principle",
          "timestamp": "17:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Amram citing Rav Nachman: distinguishing between gifts to oneself and gifts to others in interpreting makom peiri",
          "display_title": "Self-Interest Distinction",
          "timestamp": "21:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Comparison to Reish Lakish's case of selling a house while retaining the upper floor and air rights",
          "display_title": "House/Upper Floor Case",
          "timestamp": "24:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: only concrete transfers work; abstract fruit cannot transfer but retained fruit implies retained property",
          "display_title": "Concrete Transfer Rule",
          "timestamp": "27:23"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Kol Nechasav vs. Miktzat Nechasav: When Matnat Shchiv Mera Applies",
      "display_title": "Kol/Miktzat Nechasav",
      "timestamp": "29:40",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Yosef bar Minyumi's statement: matnat shchiv mera requires giving all property; partial gifts are ordinary kinyan",
          "display_title": "Kol Nechasav Requirement",
          "timestamp": "29:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinction between k'mechaleik (one process of distribution) and b'nimlach (separate sequential acts)",
          "display_title": "Mechaleik vs. Nimlach",
          "timestamp": "30:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "The consequence: if sequential, only the last recipient gets matnat shchiv mera status with amad chozer",
          "display_title": "Last Recipient Status",
          "timestamp": "32:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's concern: how do we ever know if it's truly kol nechasav, given possibility of hidden assets elsewhere",
          "display_title": "Hidden Assets Concern",
          "timestamp": "35:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Chama's answer: explicit language of 'all my property' or Rabbeinu Chananel's view on what constitutes kol nechasav",
          "display_title": "Explicit Language Soluti…",
          "timestamp": "36:42"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Chazara B'Miktzat: When Modification of One Piece Revokes the Entire Gift",
      "display_title": "Chazara B'Miktzat",
      "timestamp": "40:29",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Iba'ya lehu: does changing one piece of a matnat shchiv mera retract everything or just that piece",
          "display_title": "Retraction Question",
          "timestamp": "40:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Braita: sheni kana rishon lo kana—if later recipient gets something the first gets nothing",
          "display_title": "Braita Evidence",
          "timestamp": "42:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's initial hypothesis: if the giver retained ninety-five percent perhaps it's not a full retraction",
          "display_title": "Retention Hypothesis",
          "timestamp": "45:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Yimar to Rav Ashi: if first case is amad, why doesn't that explain both cases",
          "display_title": "Amad Question",
          "timestamp": "50:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Final resolution: chazara b'miktzat is indeed chazara b'kula—modifying one piece completely retracts the original gift",
          "display_title": "Final Resolution",
          "timestamp": "51:36"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
